	id="Illu_PastingLemma">
	<title>Pasting Lemma: Illustration</title>
	<sub.page.body>
		<block>
			<para>The essence of the Pasting Lemma is illustrated in the graphic below.</para>
			<figure>
				<img src="ims/PastingLemma.png"></img><!-- svg available -->
			</figure>
			<para>We start with two functions:</para>
			<ul>
				<li><para><latex>{\color{red} f\from \OCIntrvl{a}{b}\to \RNr}</latex>, and</para></li>
				<li><para><latex>{\color{blue} g\from \COIntrvl{b}{c}\to \RNr}</latex>.</para></li>
			</ul>
			<para>Now there is a two-step process which gives new information:</para>
			<ol>
				<li><para>If <latex>{\color{red} f(b)} = {\color{blue} g(b)}</latex>, then <latex>f</latex> and <latex>g</latex> can be pasted together to form a new function</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>h\from \OOIntrvl{a}{c} \longrightarrow \RNr</latex>
				</math.display>
				</li>
				<li>
					<para>If <latex>f</latex> and <latex>g</latex> are both continuous at <latex>b</latex>, so is <latex>h</latex>. &ndash; Visibly: under this condition the pasted function does not make a jump at <latex>b</latex>.</para>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</block>
	</sub.page.body>
</sub.page>